The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | IDBI bears brunt of bad loans
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       IDBI bears brunt of bad loans
                            
	Mumbai, July 22 (PTI): Mounting bad loans and declining non-interest income have hit the first-quarter numbers of Industrial Development Bank of India (IDBI).        
	For the quarter ended June 30, this year, the lender has posted a 4 per cent growth in net profit at Rs 160 crore against Rs 153 crore in the same period a year ago, IDBI said in a statement here today.        
	The net non-performing assets of the bank, during the quarter, escalated 1.36 per cent to Rs 1,071 crore compared with Rs 714 crore in the corresponding period a year ago, the bank said.        
	Gross non-performing assets in the first quarter of 2008-09 stood at Rs 1,578 crore against Rs 1,294 crore in the previous year.        
	The total income rose to Rs 2,739.12 crore in the latest quarter from Rs 2,193 crore in the year-ago period.        
	Non-interest income in the latest quarter declined to Rs 322 crore from Rs 400 crore in the same period last year, while interest income posted a marginal increase at Rs 2,418 crore against Rs 1,793 crore, the lender said.        
	Meanwhile, the bank has posted an impressive 56 per cent growth in deposits during the quarter that grew to Rs 72,717 crore as against Rs 46,757 crore.        
	Advances, during the period under review, went up to Rs 78,115 crore, up 31 per cent, compared with Rs 59,772 crore in June-end last year, the bank said. The total business of the bank has reached Rs 1,50,832 crore against Rs 1,06,529 crore a year ago, the bank added. Total provisions in the first quarter stood at Rs 19.88 crore compared with Rs 85.73 crore in the previous fiscal.                                                                                                                                     
